{"title_page": "Spencer Brown (rugby union, born 1973)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{infobox rugby biography\n| name           = Spencer Brown\n| image          =Spencer Brown vs NZ 1997.jpg \n| image_size     =\n| caption        =Spencer Brown attacking for England against New Zealand at Leicester's Welford Road in 1997.\n| alt            =\n| birth_name     = Spencer Brown\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1973|7|11}}\n| birth_place    = Eton, England\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = 5 ft 11 in\n| weight         = 14 st 0 lb\n| school         =\n| university     = BSc, University of Northampton    MSc, University of Edinburgh     PhD, University of Warwick\n| spouse         =\n| children       = Olivia Catherine Brown\n| relatives      =\n| occupation     =Physical Performance Coach\n| ru_currentteam         =\n| ru_position            = [[Rugby union positions#14. 11. & 15. Wing|Wing]]\n| ru_youthyears          = &nbsp;\n| ru_youthclubs          =\n| ru_clubyears           = 1992\u20131999<br>1999\u20132001<br>2002\u20132005\n| ru_proclubs            = [[Richmond RFC|Richmond]]<br>[[Bristol RFC]]<br>[[Bedford Blues]]\n| ru_clubcaps            =\n| ru_clubpoints          =\n| ru_clubupdate          =\n| ru_provinceyears       =\n| ru_province            =\n| ru_provincecaps        =\n| ru_provincepoints      =\n| super14years           = &nbsp;\n| super14                =\n| super14caps            =\n| super14points          =\n| ru_nationalyears       = 1998\n| ru_nationalteam        = {{flagicon|England}} [[England national rugby union team|England]]<br> {{flagicon|England}} [[England Sevens team|England Sevens]]<br> [[Conbined Services rugby union team|Combined Services]]<br> [[Royal Navy rugby union team|Royal Navy]]\n| ru_nationalcaps        = 3\n| ru_nationalpoints      = (0)\n| ru_ntupdate            =\n| ru_sevensnationalyears = &nbsp;\n| ru_sevensnationalteam  =\n| ru_sevensnationalcomp  =\n| ru_coachyears          =\n| ru_coachclubs          =\n| ru_refereeyears        =\n| ru_refereecomps        =\n| ru_refereeapps         =\n}}\n'''Spencer Brown''' (born 11 July 1973, Eton, England) is a former professional and International [[rugby union]] player. He played on the wing and at fullback.\n\nSpencer appeared on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] programme ''[[Long Lost Family (UK TV series)|Long Lost Family]]'' in August 2018.<ref> {{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-6032595/Former-England-rugby-player-Spencer-Brown-appears-Long-Lost-Family.html|title=Former England rugby player Spencer Brown is reunited with his family|last=Pike|first=Molly Rose|date=2018-08-08|website=Mail Online|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>{{better source|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Biography==\nSpencer Brown was a professional rugby player as a [[Rugby union positions#14. 11. & 15. Wing|winger/fullback]] for nine years, with six of these being in the English premiership for [[Richmond RFC]] and [[Bristol RFC]]. Brown has also represented the Royal Navy and Combined Services rugby teams. His professional career ended at [[Bedford Blues]] where he was later to become the strength and conditioning coach. He joined [[Richmond RFC]] in 1992 when they were in the third tier of English rugby. His professional debut for [[Richmond RFC]] came on 7 September 1997 in the Challenge Cup in the 34-18 defeat to Colomiers. He then moved to [[Bristol RFC]] after the 1998-1999 season - Bristol rugby fans first saw his defensive qualities when he made a bone crunching try saving tackle on [[Tana Umaga]] whilst playing against New Zealand for an England XV team at [[Ashton Gate Stadium|Ashton Gate]]. Brown was a member of the England Elite squad between 1998 and 2001 during which time he represented England at the World Sevens in Paris, England 'A' during three seasons, and won two full England caps against Australia and South Africa on the 1998 tour to the Southern Hemisphere.\n\nHe joined the Royal Marines as a Musician in 1990 and served for 13 years. During this time he was based at RAF Northolt, Deal, London, Bristol and Portsmouth. He has a 1st class Honours Degree in Sport & Exercise Science from The [[University of Northampton]], a Master's Degree in Strength & Conditioning from The [[University of Edinburgh]], a PhD in Health Sciences from The [[University of Warwick]], and has a solo pilot's licence. He is a former Director of Peak Performance Center of Excellence Ltd, a Strength & Conditioning and Injury Rehabilitation Center based in Rugby, Warwickshire, and is a consultant in strength & conditioning at the Derby Nuffield Health Hospital. Brown has also worked with talented athletes as part of the Strength & Conditioning staff at the Derbyshire Institute of Sport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scrum.com/england/rugby/player/12860.html|title=Spencer Brown |publisher=scrum.com|accessdate=6 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ppcoe.co.uk/|title=Default Parallels Plesk Panel Page|website=www.ppcoe.co.uk|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref>\n\nSpencer, along with fellow rugby player Mark Dunkley, are co-founders of RugbyFestUK. This annual event is designed to be the biggest celebration of the game staged outside of a major tournament and was first held on 22 \u2013 24 September 2017, [[Rugby, Warwickshire]], [[England]] with proceeds shared among five charities including the [[Wooden Spoon Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rugbyfestuk.com|title=Home - RugbyFestUK|website=RugbyFestUK|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-01}}</ref>\n\nSpencer now runs a sports performance and injury rehabilitation business in Bermuda, playing rugby for the Bermuda Police Rugby Football Club, where he also works as strength and conditioning coach. He was reunited with his birth mother in early 2018 and appeared on ITV's [[Long Lost Family (British TV series)|Long-Lost Family]] later that year to be reunited with his sister.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Spencer}}\n[[Category:Richmond F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol Bears players]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rugby union wings]]\n[[Category:English rugby union players]]\n[[Category:England international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Black British sportspeople]]\n[[Category:English people of Jamaican descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{infobox rugby biography\n| name           = Spencer Brown\n| image          =Spencer Brown vs NZ 1997.jpg \n| image_size     =\n| caption        =Spencer Brown attacking for England against New Zealand at Leicester's Welford Road in 1997.\n| alt            =\n| birth_name     = Spencer Brown\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1973|7|11}}\n| birth_place    = Eton, England\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| height         = 5 ft 11 in\n| weight         = 14 st 0 lb\n| school         =\n| university     = BSc, University of Northampton; MSc, University of Edinburgh; PhD, University of Warwick\n| spouse         =\n| children       = Olivia Catherine Brown\n| relatives      =\n| occupation     =Physical Performance Coach\n| ru_currentteam         =\n| ru_position            = [[Rugby union positions#14. 11. & 15. Wing|Wing]]\n| ru_youthyears          = &nbsp;\n| ru_youthclubs          =\n| ru_clubyears           = 1992\u20131999<br>1999\u20132001<br>2002\u20132005\n| ru_proclubs            = [[Richmond RFC|Richmond]]<br>[[Bristol RFC]]<br>[[Bedford Blues]]\n| ru_clubcaps            =\n| ru_clubpoints          =\n| ru_clubupdate          =\n| ru_provinceyears       =\n| ru_province            =\n| ru_provincecaps        =\n| ru_provincepoints      =\n| super14years           = &nbsp;\n| super14                =\n| super14caps            =\n| super14points          =\n| ru_nationalyears       = 1998\n| ru_nationalteam        = {{flagicon|England}} [[England national rugby union team|England]]<br> {{flagicon|England}} [[England Sevens team|England Sevens]]<br> [[Conbined Services rugby union team|Combined Services]]<br> [[Royal Navy rugby union team|Royal Navy]]\n| ru_nationalcaps        = 3\n| ru_nationalpoints      = (0)\n| ru_ntupdate            =\n| ru_sevensnationalyears = &nbsp;\n| ru_sevensnationalteam  =\n| ru_sevensnationalcomp  =\n| ru_coachyears          =\n| ru_coachclubs          =\n| ru_refereeyears        =\n| ru_refereecomps        =\n| ru_refereeapps         =\n}}\n'''Spencer Brown''' (born 11 July 1973, Eton, England) is a former professional and International [[rugby union]] player. He played on the wing and at fullback.\n\nSpencer appeared on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] programme ''[[Long Lost Family (UK TV series)|Long Lost Family]]'' in August 2018.<ref> {{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-6032595/Former-England-rugby-player-Spencer-Brown-appears-Long-Lost-Family.html|title=Former England rugby player Spencer Brown is reunited with his family|last=Pike|first=Molly Rose|date=2018-08-08|website=Mail Online|access-date=2020-01-09}}</ref>{{better source|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Biography==\nSpencer Brown was a professional rugby player as a [[Rugby union positions#14. 11. & 15. Wing|winger/fullback]] for nine years, with six of these being in the English premiership for [[Richmond RFC]] and [[Bristol RFC]]. Brown has also represented the Royal Navy and Combined Services rugby teams. His professional career ended at [[Bedford Blues]] where he was later to become the strength and conditioning coach. He joined [[Richmond RFC]] in 1992 when they were in the third tier of English rugby. His professional debut for [[Richmond RFC]] came on 7 September 1997 in the Challenge Cup in the 34-18 defeat to Colomiers. He then moved to [[Bristol RFC]] after the 1998-1999 season - Bristol rugby fans first saw his defensive qualities when he made a bone crunching try saving tackle on [[Tana Umaga]] whilst playing against New Zealand for an England XV team at [[Ashton Gate Stadium|Ashton Gate]]. Brown was a member of the England Elite squad between 1998 and 2001 during which time he represented England at the World Sevens in Paris, England 'A' during three seasons, and won two full England caps against Australia and South Africa on the 1998 tour to the Southern Hemisphere.\n\nHe joined the Royal Marines as a Musician in 1990 and served for 13 years. During this time he was based at RAF Northolt, Deal, London, Bristol and Portsmouth. He has a 1st class Honours Degree in Sport & Exercise Science from The [[University of Northampton]], a Master's Degree in Strength & Conditioning from The [[University of Edinburgh]], a PhD in Health Sciences from The [[University of Warwick]], and has a solo pilot's licence. He is a former Director of Peak Performance Center of Excellence Ltd, a Strength & Conditioning and Injury Rehabilitation Center based in Rugby, Warwickshire, and is a consultant in strength & conditioning at the Derby Nuffield Health Hospital. Brown has also worked with talented athletes as part of the Strength & Conditioning staff at the Derbyshire Institute of Sport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scrum.com/england/rugby/player/12860.html|title=Spencer Brown |publisher=scrum.com|accessdate=6 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ppcoe.co.uk/|title=Default Parallels Plesk Panel Page|website=www.ppcoe.co.uk|access-date=2019-07-11}}</ref>\n\nSpencer, along with fellow rugby player Mark Dunkley, are co-founders of RugbyFestUK. This annual event is designed to be the biggest celebration of the game staged outside of a major tournament and was first held on 22 \u2013 24 September 2017, [[Rugby, Warwickshire]], [[England]] with proceeds shared among five charities including the [[Wooden Spoon Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rugbyfestuk.com|title=Home - RugbyFestUK|website=RugbyFestUK|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-01}}</ref>\n\nSpencer now runs a sports performance and injury rehabilitation business in Bermuda, playing rugby for the Bermuda Police Rugby Football Club, where he also works as strength and conditioning coach. He was reunited with his birth mother in early 2018 and appeared on ITV's [[Long Lost Family (British TV series)|Long-Lost Family]] later that year to be reunited with his sister.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Spencer}}\n[[Category:Richmond F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bristol Bears players]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rugby union wings]]\n[[Category:English rugby union players]]\n[[Category:England international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Black British sportspeople]]\n[[Category:English people of Jamaican descent]]\n", "name_user": "PeakPerformanceSB", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spencer_Brown_(rugby_union,_born_1973)"}
{"title_page": "No Borders Here", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = No Borders Here\n| type         = Studio album\n| artist       = [[Jane Siberry]]\n| cover        = No Borders Here (Jane Siberry album - cover art).jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = 1984\n| recorded     = 1983-1984\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Progressive Pop]], [[Ambient pop|Ambient Pop]], [[New wave music|New Wave]]\n| length       = 42:32\n| label        = [[Duke Street Records]]/[[Open Air Records]]/[[Windham Hill Records]]\n| producer     = [[Jonathan Goldsmith (musician)|Jon Goldsmith]], [[Kerry Crawford]], [[Jane Siberry]], and [[John Switzer]]\n| prev_title   = [[Jane Siberry (album)|Jane Siberry]]\n| prev_year    = 1981\n| next_title   = [[The Speckless Sky]]\n| next_year    = 1985\n| misc         = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Canadian LP cover\n | type    = Studio album\n | cover   = jsnbhcan.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}} <ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r17943}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[Robert Christgau]]\n| rev2Score =  (B-) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=jane+siberry |title=CG: jane siberry |publisher=Robert Christgau |date= |accessdate=2012-03-03}}</ref>\n\n}}\n'''''No Borders Here''''' is the second [[album]] (and first to be available outside [[Canada]]) by [[Jane Siberry]].\n\nThe album's single \"[[Mimi on the Beach]]\" was Siberry's breakthrough hit in her native Canada, and remains one of her most famous songs. [[Toronto]]'s [[CFNY-FM|CFNY]] was the first radio station in Canada to recognize the song's hit potential.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} The song's video was also one of the first influential clips on [[MuchMusic]].\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs by [[Jane Siberry]], except as noted.\n# \"The Waitress\" \u2013 2:25\n# \"I Muse Aloud\" \u2013 4:11\n# \"Dancing Class\" \u2013 6:41\n# \"Extra Executives\" (Siberry, [[John Switzer]]) \u2013 4:26\n# \"You Don't Need\" \u2013 4:25\n# \"Symmetry (The Way Things Have to Be)\" \u2013 4:57\n# \"Follow Me\" \u2013 4:19\n# \"[[Mimi on the Beach]]\" \u2013 7:35\n# \"Map of the World, Pt. 1\" \u2013 3:33\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Jane Siberry]] \u2013 [[guitar]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[Singing|vocals]]\n*[[Al Cross]] \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]], [[LinnDrum]]\n*[[Ken Myhr]] \u2013 guitar\n*[[John Switzer]] \u2013 [[bass guitar|bass]], percussion\n\n===Additional personnel===\n*[[Jonathan Goldsmith (musician)|Jon Goldsmith]] \u2013 keyboards\n*[[Doug Wilde]] \u2013 keyboards\n*[[Rob Yale]] \u2013 [[Fairlight CMI]] programming\n\n==Chart positions==\n* ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' - 68<ref>[http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.8715&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=ccntousk30frf6h4jsn237nm12 Top Albums/CDs - Volume 41, No. 5, October 06 1984].</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Jane Siberry}}\n\n[[Category:Jane Siberry albums]]\n[[Category:1984 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jane Siberry]]\n[[Category:Duke Street Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = No Borders Here\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[Jane Siberry]]\n| cover      = No Borders Here (Jane Siberry album - cover art).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1984\n| recorded   = 1983-1984\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]], [[Ambient music|ambient pop]], [[New wave music|new wave]], [[post-punk]]\n| length     = 42:32\n| label      = [[Duke Street Records]]/[[Open Air Records]]/[[Windham Hill Records]]\n| producer   = [[Jonathan Goldsmith (musician)|Jon Goldsmith]], [[Kerry Crawford]], [[Jane Siberry]], and [[John Switzer]]\n| prev_title = [[Jane Siberry (album)|Jane Siberry]]\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = [[The Speckless Sky]]\n| next_year  = 1985\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Canadian LP cover\n | type    = Studio album\n | cover   = jsnbhcan.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}} <ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r17943}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[Robert Christgau]]\n| rev2Score =  (B-) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=jane+siberry |title=CG: jane siberry |publisher=Robert Christgau |date= |accessdate=2012-03-03}}</ref>\n\n}}\n'''''No Borders Here''''' is the second [[album]] (and first to be available outside [[Canada]]) by [[Jane Siberry]].\n\nThe album's single \"[[Mimi on the Beach]]\" was Siberry's breakthrough hit in her native Canada, and remains one of her most famous songs. [[Toronto]]'s [[CFNY-FM|CFNY]] was the first radio station in Canada to recognize the song's hit potential.{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}} The song's video was also one of the first influential clips on [[MuchMusic]].\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs by [[Jane Siberry]], except as noted.\n# \"The Waitress\" \u2013 2:25\n# \"I Muse Aloud\" \u2013 4:11\n# \"Dancing Class\" \u2013 6:41\n# \"Extra Executives\" (Siberry, [[John Switzer]]) \u2013 4:26\n# \"You Don't Need\" \u2013 4:25\n# \"Symmetry (The Way Things Have to Be)\" \u2013 4:57\n# \"Follow Me\" \u2013 4:19\n# \"[[Mimi on the Beach]]\" \u2013 7:35\n# \"Map of the World, Pt. 1\" \u2013 3:33\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Jane Siberry]] \u2013 [[guitar]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[Singing|vocals]]\n*[[Al Cross]] \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]], [[LinnDrum]]\n*[[Ken Myhr]] \u2013 guitar\n*[[John Switzer]] \u2013 [[bass guitar|bass]], percussion\n\n===Additional personnel===\n*[[Jonathan Goldsmith (musician)|Jon Goldsmith]] \u2013 keyboards\n*[[Doug Wilde]] \u2013 keyboards\n*[[Rob Yale]] \u2013 [[Fairlight CMI]] programming\n\n==Chart positions==\n* ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' - 68<ref>[http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.8715&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=ccntousk30frf6h4jsn237nm12 Top Albums/CDs - Volume 41, No. 5, October 06 1984].</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Jane Siberry}}\n\n[[Category:Jane Siberry albums]]\n[[Category:1984 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jane Siberry]]\n[[Category:Duke Street Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "Sneezybaba", "label": "safe", "comment": "Genres corrected.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No_Borders_Here"}
{"title_page": "Yaakov Tzvi Mecklenburg", "text_new": "[[File:Yaacov Zvi Meklenburg cropped.jpg|right|thumb|Yaacov Zvi Meklenburg. Assumed to be a commercially produced reproduction, Germany, c. last quarter of the nineteenth century]]\n'''Yaakov Tzvi Mecklenburg''' (\u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05e6\u05d1\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05e0\u05d1\u05d5\u05e8\u05d2) was a [[Germany|German]] [[rabbi]] and scholar of the 19th century, best known as author of the [[Torah commentaries|Torah commentary]] ''Haketav VehaKabbalah'' (''HaKsav VeHaKabalah'').\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in 1785 (5545) in Lissa ([[Leszno]]), in the province of [[Grand Duchy of Posen|Posen]], [[Germany]], in the family of Rabbi Gamliel.  At the time, Lissa was a famous center of Torah studies, and Mecklenburg began [[Torah study|studying Torah]] as a student of the local ''Rav'', [[Zechariah Mendel]], a friend and correspondent of Rabbi [[Akiva Eger]]. Zechariah Mendel was the son of [[David Tebla]], the previous Rav of Lissa.<ref name=\"tzvi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hevratpinto.org/tzadikim_eng/109_rabbi_yaakov_tzvi_mecklenburg.html|title=Rabbi Yaakov Tzvi Mecklenburg|publisher=Hevrat Pinto|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nR. Mecklenburg initially thereafter went into business. In 1831, at the age of 46, following commercial difficulties, he decided to quit business and was offered the rabbinical position in the city of [[K\u00f6nigsberg]], [[East Prussia]]. At that time, Koenigsburg Jews were under the increasing influence of the [[Haskalah]], a reform movement, which Yaakov Tzvi Mecklenburg strongly opposed.<ref name=\"tzvi\"/> Together with the [[Malbim]], he publicly opposed [[Reform Judaism]]'s 1844 [[Braunschweig]]  [https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0017_0_16262.html convention]. In the same period, he wrote ''Haketav VehaKabbalah'', his own commentary to the Torah.\n\nHe served as Rabbi in K\u00f6nigsberg, for the rest of his life, for 34 years (1831\u201365). Before his death, he ordered that no [[hesped|eulogies]] be given at his funeral. In his will, he requested that ''Haketav Vehakabbalah'' be read after the public [[Torah reading]], during the [[shloshim|first 30 days of mourning]].<ref name=\"tzvi\"/>\n\nIn the opinion of others, Rabbi Yaakov Tzvi studied directly under Rabbi Akiva Eiger.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} He mentions in his ''Haketav Vehakabbaleh'' Rabbi A. Eiger a few times as 'my Mentor and Teacher'.\nExample: In Leviticus 27:32, he states: I asked my Mentor and Teacher Rabbi Akiva Eger, etc..\n\n==Works==\n[[Image:HaKsav VeHaKabalah.jpg|thumb|150px|A modern edition of ''Haketav VehaKabbalah''.]]\n\n'''''Haketav VehaKabbalah''''' (alt. ''HaKsav VeHaKabalah''; Heb. \u05d4\u05db\u05ea\u05d1 \u05d5\u05d4\u05e7\u05d1\u05dc\u05d4: The Written [Torah] and the [Oral] Tradition) was first published in 1839. Mecklenburg's intent was \"to demonstrate the indivisibility of the written Torah and its counterpart, the [[oral Torah]]\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Haketav-Vehakabbalah-Demonstrating-Indivisibility-Commentaries/dp/9657108292|title=Editorial review at Amazon|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref> His explanations thus connect the literal meaning (''[[peshat]]'') to the hidden meaning (''[[Pardes (Jewish exegesis)#Derash .28Midrash.29|derash]]''), focusing on the traditional Jewish sources (the [[Mishna]], the [[Talmud]], and the [[Midrash]]).<ref name=\"tzvi\"/> The commentary draws on that of the [[Vilna Gaon]] and [[Shadal]]<ref>{{daat enc|id1=3247|he-title=\u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05e0\u05d1\u05d5\u05e8\u05d2 \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05e6\u05d1\u05d9|trans-title=Mecklenburg, Yaakov Tzvi}}</ref> and occasionally includes contemporary non-traditional sources such as [[Julius F\u00fcrst]] and the [[Biurists]]. See [[Oral Torah #In rabbinic literature and commentary]].\n\nOther works include:\n*''Iyun Tefillah'' -  a commentary on the ''[[Siddur]]'', usually coupled with ''Derech HaChaim'' written by R. Yaakov Lorberbaum of Lisa.\n*''Hishtapchut HaNefesh''  - ''[[viduy]]'' (confessional prayers) for the eve of [[Yom Kippur]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hevratpinto.org/tzadikim_eng/109_rabbi_yaakov_tzvi_mecklenburg.html Rabbi Yaakov Tzvi Mecklenburg - \u201cThe Author of Haketav Vehakabbalah\u201d], Hevrat Pinto\n*[http://www.etz-hayim.com/commentators/commentator.php?id=jacob-tzvi-mecklenburg Jacob Tzvi Mecklenburg], Etz Hayim\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mecklenburg, Yaakov}}\n[[Category:Later Acharonim]]\n[[Category:19th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:Chief rabbis of cities]]\n[[Category:German Orthodox rabbis]]\n[[Category:Bible commentators]]\n[[Category:1785 births]]\n[[Category:1865 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Yaacov Zvi Meklenburg cropped.jpg|right|thumb|Yaacov Zvi Meklenburg. Assumed to be a commercially produced reproduction, Germany, c. last quarter of the nineteenth century]]\n'''Yaakov Tzvi Mecklenburg''' (\u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05e6\u05d1\u05d9 \u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05e0\u05d1\u05d5\u05e8\u05d2) was a [[Germany|German]] [[rabbi]] and scholar of the 19th century, best known as author of the [[Torah commentaries|Torah commentary]] ''Haketav VehaKabbalah'' (''HaKsav VeHaKabalah'').\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in 1785 (5545) in Lissa ([[Leszno]]), in the province of [[Grand Duchy of Posen|Posen]], [[Germany]], in the family of Rabbi Gamliel.  At the time, Lissa was a famous center of Torah studies, and Mecklenburg began [[Torah study|studying Torah]] as a student of the local ''Rav'', [[Zechariah Mendel]], a friend and correspondent of Rabbi [[Akiva Eger]]. Zechariah Mendel was the son of [[David Tebla]], the previous Rav of Lissa.<ref name=\"tzvi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hevratpinto.org/tzadikim_eng/109_rabbi_yaakov_tzvi_mecklenburg.html|title=Rabbi Yaakov Tzvi Mecklenburg|publisher=Hevrat Pinto|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nR. Mecklenburg initially thereafter went into business. In 1831, at the age of 46, following commercial difficulties, he decided to quit business and was offered the rabbinical position in the city of [[K\u00f6nigsberg]], [[East Prussia]]. At that time, Koenigsburg Jews were under the increasing influence of the [[Haskalah]], a reform movement, which Yaakov Tzvi Mecklenburg strongly opposed.<ref name=\"tzvi\"/> Together with the [[Malbim]], he publicly opposed [[Reform Judaism]]'s 1844 [[Braunschweig]]  [https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0017_0_16262.html convention]. In the same period, he wrote ''Haketav VehaKabbalah'', his own commentary to the Torah.\n\nHe served as Rabbi in K\u00f6nigsberg, for the rest of his life, for 34 years (1831\u201365). Before his death, he ordered that no [[hesped|eulogies]] be given at his funeral. In his will, he requested that ''Haketav Vehakabbalah'' be read after the public [[Torah reading]], during the [[shloshim|first 30 days of mourning]].<ref name=\"tzvi\"/>\n\nIn the opinion of others, Rabbi Yaakov Tzvi studied directly under Rabbi Akiva Eiger.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} He mentions in his ''Haketav Vehakabbaleh'' Rabbi A. Eiger a few times as 'my Mentor and Teacher'.\nExample: In Leviticus 27:32, he states: I asked my Mentor and Teacher Rabbi Akiva Eger, etc..\n\n==Works==\n[[Image:HaKsav VeHaKabalah.jpg|thumb|150px|A modern edition of ''Haketav VehaKabbalah''.]]\n\n'''''Haketav VehaKabbalah''''' (alt. ''HaKsav VeHaKabalah''; Heb. \u05d4\u05db\u05ea\u05d1 \u05d5\u05d4\u05e7\u05d1\u05dc\u05d4: The Written [Torah] and the [Oral] Tradition) was first published in 1839. Mecklenburg's intent was \"to demonstrate the indivisibility of the written Torah and its counterpart, the [[oral Torah]]\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Haketav-Vehakabbalah-Demonstrating-Indivisibility-Commentaries/dp/9657108292|title=Editorial review at Amazon|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref> His explanations thus connect the literal meaning (''[[peshat]]'') to the hidden meaning (''[[Pardes (Jewish exegesis)#Derash .28Midrash.29|derash]]''), focusing on the traditional Jewish sources (the [[Mishna]], the [[Talmud]], and the [[Midrash]]).<ref name=\"tzvi\"/> The commentary draws on that of the [[Vilna Gaon]] and [[Shadal]] <ref>{{daat enc|id1=3247|he-title=\u05de\u05e7\u05dc\u05e0\u05d1\u05d5\u05e8\u05d2 \u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05e6\u05d1\u05d9|trans-title=Mecklenburg, Yaakov Tzvi}}</ref> and occasionally includes contemporary non-traditional sources such as [[Julius F\u00fcrst]] and the [[Biurists]]. See [[Oral Torah #In rabbinic literature and commentary]].\n\nOther works include:\n*''Iyun Tefillah'' -  a commentary on the ''[[Siddur]]'', usually coupled with ''Derech HaChaim'' written by R. Yaakov Lorberbaum of Lisa.\n*''Hishtapchut HaNefesh''  - ''[[viduy]]'' (confessional prayers) for the eve of [[Yom Kippur]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hevratpinto.org/tzadikim_eng/109_rabbi_yaakov_tzvi_mecklenburg.html Rabbi Yaakov Tzvi Mecklenburg - \u201cThe Author of Haketav Vehakabbalah\u201d], Hevrat Pinto\n*[http://www.etz-hayim.com/commentators/commentator.php?id=jacob-tzvi-mecklenburg Jacob Tzvi Mecklenburg], Etz Hayim\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mecklenburg, Yaakov}}\n[[Category:Later Acharonim]]\n[[Category:19th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:Chief rabbis of cities]]\n[[Category:German Orthodox rabbis]]\n[[Category:Bible commentators]]\n[[Category:1785 births]]\n[[Category:1865 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "TRM001", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorks:grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yaakov_Tzvi_Mecklenburg"}
{"title_page": "Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)", "text_new": "{{short description|Professional wrestling company}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name=Universal Wrestling Federation\n|image=[[File:Logo of the defunct Universal Wrestling Federation owned by Herb Abrams from 1990-1996.jpg|220px]]\n|type=[[Private company|Private]]\n|fate=Assets acquired by Al Burke\n|foundation=August 26, 1990\n|defunct=July 23, 1996\n|founder=[[Herb Abrams]]\n|area_served = Worldwide\n|location=[[Marina del Rey, California]]\n|industry=[[Professional wrestling]]\n|products=Television, Merchandise\n}}\n\n'''Universal Wrestling Federation''' ('''UWF''') was an American [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] owned by [[Herb Abrams]] from 1990 to 1996. The company aired nationally on [[SportsChannel America]], and later on [[Prime Ticket]] and [[ESPN2]]. \n\nA Season 2 episode of ''[[Dark Side of the Ring]]'' focused on the promotion will air in May 2020.<ref>https://www.tvinsider.com/927543/dark-side-of-the-ring-season-2-premiere-chris-benoit/</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Herb Abrams]] founded the UWF in 1990 to try and challenge [[Vince McMahon]]'s [[World Wrestling Federation]] on a national level. He announced the promotion's formation at John Arezzi's ''Wrestling Fans Fantasy Weekend'' convention in August 1990. Despite having no experience in the wrestling business, Abrams was given a budget of $1 million by [[SportsChannel America]] to develop a weekly television series, which would become ''Fury Hour''.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 134.</ref> The first ''Fury Hour'' tapings were held at [[Reseda Country Club]] in the Fall of 1990 and featured established stars such as [[Paul Orndorff]], [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]], [[Don Muraco]], [[Bob Orton, Jr.]], [[Brian Blair]], [[Dan Spivey]], [[Billy Jack Haynes]], [[Ken Patera]], [[Colonel DeBeers]], [[David Sammartino]], [[Ivan Koloff]], and [[Mick Foley|Cactus Jack]].<ref name=mf184>Foley, Mick. Have A Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks (p.184)</ref> The top homegrown talent included \"Wild Thing\" Steve Ray and \"Cutie Pie\" [[Louie Spicolli]]. [[Bruno Sammartino]] and [[Lou Albano]] were hired as commentators.\n\nThe promotion held a taping in [[New York City]] at the [[New York Penta]] in January 1991 that was plagued with legal issues. The World Wrestling Federation sent cease and desist orders after [[The Honky Tonk Man|Honky Tonk Man]] and [[Rick Rude]] appeared on-camera.<ref name=02041991WON>{{cite web|url=https://members.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-newsletter/feb-4-1991-observer-newsletter-pivotal-week-life-dave-meltzer-89881|title=February 4, 1991 Observer Newsletter: Pivotal week in the life of Dave Meltzer|author=Observer Staff|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|website=F4WOnline.com|date=February 4, 1991|accessdate=September 7, 2019}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Both had recently walked out of the WWF but were still under contract to the company. Honky Tonk Man would later explain that the check he received from Abrams for this taping bounced, and he filed a formal complaint with the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] to get reimbursed.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9r6kIfzFSSM</ref>\n\nAbrams hired Howard Brody, the owner of [[Ladies Major League Wrestling]], to help him expand UWF into the Florida market in mid-1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 149.</ref> Following several house shows and a television taping at [[Universal Studios Florida]], Brody was entrusted with finding a venue for the promotion's first [[pay per view]] event in June 1991. Brody suggested the [[Odeum Expo Center]] in Chicago. Abrams insisted on holding [[Beach Brawl]] at [[Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, FL]].<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 156.</ref> The pay per view was a disaster in both attendance and pay per view buys. Following Beach Brawl, Abrams ran one final television taping in Florida before running out of fresh footage for ''Fury Hour''. He struck a deal with Brody to use footage from Ladies Major League Wrestling to fulfill his obligations with SportsChannel America, and the two parted ways in the Fall of 1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 163.</ref>\n\nAbrams would only run three more shows after his initial SportsChannel America deal expired in late 1991. This included a television taping at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] in June 1992 that aired on [[Prime Ticket]] as ''Thunder Hour'', a television taping at [[North Dakota State Fair]] in July 1993 that was never aired, and the [[Blackjack Brawl]] show at [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in September 1994. The latter show aired live on SportsChannel America and was a disaster in both attendance and television ratings.\n\nAbrams left for New York City to take care of his ailing mother in December 1994, and wrestler Al Burke was put in charge of the company.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewalburke.htm</ref> [[Zoogz Rift]] also worked for the company during this time, and claimed Abrams' addiction to [[cocaine]] drained the company of money needed to do further shows.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm</ref> [[ESPN2]] aired old episodes of ''Fury Hour'' and ''Thunder Hour'' in 1995, albeit in heavily edited form. Abrams died of a heart attack in July 1996 while still in New York.\n\nAl Burke claimed ownership of the UWF tape library as abandoned property following the death of Abrams. In recent years, Burke partnered with Todd Okerlund of Classic Wrestling to repackage and license the library through [[DirecTV]] and [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]].\n\n==Major events==\n===Beach Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Beach Brawl}}\nUWF held two major events during its run. The first event, Beach Brawl, was the only pay-per-view event in the company's history and was held on June 7, 1991 at the [[Bradenton Area Convention Center|Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, Florida]]. The event was headlined by a match between [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] and [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], which was the final round match of a sixteen-man tournament for the crowning of the first [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Champion]]. Williams defeated Bigelow to become the first SportsChannel Television Champion. The event was an overall failure with a low buyrate of 0.1 and a crowd of 500 in attendance at the arena.\n\n===Blackjack Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Blackjack Brawl}}\nAfter the failure of Beach Brawl, UWF decided to air a live television special called Blackjack Brawl on September 23, 1994 on [[SportsChannel America]], which was UWF's last major attempt to secure a major television deal and survive in the professional wrestling industry. The event was held at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. Like its predecessor Beach Brawl, the event saw very low attendance of just 600 fans and received negative response from critics and audiences for weak quality, weakly performed matches, nonsense booking and weak commentary. The event featured nine championship matches, with two vacant championships being decided at the event, and seven new championships being contested at the event. The event was headlined by a [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] match between defending champion Steve Williams and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]]. The event was received negatively by fans especially due to the main event match ending in a disqualification, and this was UWF's final show.\n\n==''Fury Hour''==\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name = UWF Fury Hour\n|image = UWF Fury Hour.JPG\n|creator = [[Herb Abrams]]\n|caption = ''UWF Fury Hour'' logo\n|picture_format = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n|camera = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multicamera setup]]\n|runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials)\n|company = Abrams Productions\n|executive_producer = Lenny Duge\n|starring = See [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel|UWF alumni]]\n|country = United States\n|location = [[Reseda Country Club]] <small>(1990)</small><br>[[New York Penta]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[Universal Studios Florida]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[War Memorial Auditorium]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] <small>(1992)</small>\n|network = [[SportsChannel America]] <small>(1990-1991)</small><br>[[Prime Ticket]] <small>(1992)</small><br>[[ESPN2]] <small>(1995)</small>\n|first_aired = October 1, 1990\n|last_aired = July 26, 1992\n|num_episodes = 69\n|list_episodes = List of UWF Fury Hour episodes\n|opentheme = \"[[The Equalizer#Music|The Equalizer Busy Equalizing]]\" by [[Stewart Copeland]]\n|website = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0821416/\n}}\n\nIn 1990, the company signed a one-year television deal with [[SportsChannel America]]. A weekly program called '''''Fury Hour''''' debuted in October 1990, and aired on Monday nights as part of the network's ''Feet, Fists and Fury'' programming block that also included [[kickboxing]] and [[boxing]].<ref>https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/90-OCR/BC-1990-09-17-OCR-Page-0043.pdf</ref>\n\nA [[Shoot (professional wrestling)|shoot]] occurred during a semifinal [[UWF Beach Brawl#SportsChannel Television Championship tournament brackets|SportsChannel Television Championship Tournament]] match between Steve Ray and [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] in May 1991. Allegedly, [[Herb Abrams]] thought Ray was sleeping with his wife and paid Williams extra money to rough Ray up during the bout. Ray would claim years later that this was a [[worked shoot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm|title=UWF - Interview - Zoogz Rift|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3lkjnUCA7tA|title=Wrestling With Wregret - UWF|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gfwX767OOPY</ref>\n\nAbrams signed a deal with [[Prime Ticket]] in June 1992 for the production and broadcast of new content.<ref>Meltzer, Dave. ''Wrestling Observer Newsletter''. July 6, 1992, p. 14.</ref> New episodes taped at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] aired as '''''Thunder Hour''''' on Sunday nights, and ''Fury Hour'' reruns began airing on Saturday mornings.\n\nIn March 1995, existing ''Fury Hour'' and ''Thunder Hour'' episodes were repackaged to a half-hour format and aired daily on [[ESPN2]]. Those same 24 repackaged episodes later re-aired on [[ESPN Classic]] in 2008 and 2009.<ref>[http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 411mania \u00bb Wrestling \u00bb TV Reports] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922193027/http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 |date=September 22, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/espnclassic.htm|title=UWF - ESPN Classic|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>Steve Ray tried suing ESPN Classic in 2014 for using his likeness during these rebroadcasts, but was unsuccessful.<ref>https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2015/04/espn-win-in-wrestling-footage-case-upheld-on-appeal-592704/</ref>\n\n[[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]] reran original one-hour format episodes of ''Fury Hour'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2004/01/21/320155.html|title=ESPN Classics Canada won't go Raw|publisher=SLAM Wrestling|date=January 21, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Commentators\n!Tenure\n|-\n|[[Herb Abrams]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|September 24, 1990 - November 11, 1990\n|-\n|[[Craig Minervini|Craig DeGeorge]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|December 6, 1990 - July 20, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[Lou Albano]] \n|April 7, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[John Tolos]] \n|June 19, 1992\n|-\n|Carlo Gianelli and John Tolos\n|July 24, 1993 - September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Commissioners===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Commissioner\n! Date started\n! Date finished\n|-\n| Arnold Ross\n| September 24, 1990\n| October 11, 1990\n|-\n| Carlo Gianelli\n| July 24, 1993\n| July 24, 1993\n|-\n| [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n| September 23, 1994\n| September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Recurring segments===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Segment\n! Segment Type\n! Host(s)\n! Years Active\n|-\n|Ask The Wrestlers\n|Interview\n|[[Herb Abrams]]\n|1990 - 1991\n|-\n|Captain Lou's Corner\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]]\n|1990 - 1991\n|-\n|To the Point\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]] and [[Herb Abrams]]\n|1991\n|-\n|Colonel Red's Corner\n|Interview\n|Colonel Red\n|1992\n|-\n|}\n\n==Championships==\n\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Americas Championship|UWF Americas Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship|UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship]] (1993)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Israeli Championship|UWF Israeli Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship|UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF MGM Grand Championship|UWF MGM Grand Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Midget World Championship|UWF Midget World Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF North American Championship|UWF North American Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Southern States Championship|UWF Southern States Championship]] (1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Championship]] (1991-1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Women's World Championship|UWF Women's World Championship]] (1991, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Tag Team Championship|UWF World Tag Team Championship]] (1994)\n\n==Home video==\nIn 1992, the UWF issued six [[VHS]] releases in the United States through Best Film & Video Corporation: ''Beach Brawl'', ''Tag Team Tandems'', ''The Best of Paul Orndorff'', ''The Lumberjack Match'', ''The Steel Cage Match'', and ''Wrestling's Greatest Champions''. In 1993, the UWF released six volumes of [[PAL]] videos in Germany through Summit International Pictures under the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" banner. They were all compilations of Fury Hour matches. The same six \"Wrestling Super Champs\" volumes were re-released in Germany through J\u00fcnger Verlag under the \"Super Wrestling\" banner.\n\nRecent years have seen the emergence of UWF [[DVD]]s in Australia through Payless Entertainment. Each of the seven [[DVD region code#4|Region 4]] DVDs contains one episode of ''Fury Hour''. The DVDs include ''Body Slammin'', ''Grand Slam'', ''Grudge Matches'', ''It's War'', ''Tag Team Madness'', ''The Main Event'', and ''Wrestling Wars''. In Germany, a [[DVD region code|Region 0]] DVD titled \"Wrestling Super 4 Champs\" was released containing two episodes of ''Fury Hour''. Also in Germany, the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" VHS compilations were re-released on DVD in six volumes as \"American History of Wrestling - UWF\".\n\n==Awards==\n*'''Wrestling Observer Newsletter'''\n**1990 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (Herb Abrams)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Promotion of the Year|Worst Promotion of the Year]] (UWF)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Show|Worst Television Show]] (Fury Hour)\n**1994 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Major Wrestling Show|Worst Major Wrestling Show]] (Blackjack Brawl)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/index.htm Herb Abrams' UWF Tribute Site]\n*[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/indy/uwf/uwfindex.html Herb Abrams' UWF] on ProWrestlingHistory.com\n*[https://archive.org/details/HerbAbramsUWF Herb Abrams' UWF] on [[Archive.org]]\n\n{{Professional wrestling in the United States}}\n{{SportsChannel America}}\n{{Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)}}\n\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1996 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:1990s American television series]]\n[[Category:1990 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Companies disestablished in 1996]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:ESPN original programming]]\n[[Category:Independent professional wrestling promotions based in California]]\n[[Category:Marina del Rey, California]]\n[[Category:Prime Sports Network]]\n[[Category:SportsChannel]]\n[[Category:Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)]]\n\n[[de:Universal Wrestling Federation#UWF (Herb Abrams)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Professional wrestling company}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name=Universal Wrestling Federation\n|image=[[File:Logo of the defunct Universal Wrestling Federation owned by Herb Abrams from 1990-1996.jpg|220px]]\n|type=[[Private company|Private]]\n|fate=Assets acquired by Al Burke\n|foundation=August 26, 1990\n|defunct=July 23, 1996\n|founder=[[Herb Abrams]]\n|area_served = Worldwide\n|location=[[Marina del Rey, California]]\n|industry=[[Professional wrestling]]\n|products=Television, Merchandise\n}}\n\n'''Universal Wrestling Federation''' ('''UWF''') was an American [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] owned by [[Herb Abrams]] from 1990 to 1996. The company aired nationally on [[SportsChannel America]], and later on [[Prime Ticket]] and [[ESPN2]]. \n\nA Season 2 episode of ''[[Dark Side of the Ring]]'' focused on the promotion will air in May 2020.<ref>https://www.tvinsider.com/927543/dark-side-of-the-ring-season-2-premiere-chris-benoit/</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Herb Abrams]] founded the UWF in 1990 to try and challenge [[Vince McMahon]]'s [[World Wrestling Federation]] on a national level. He announced the promotion's formation at John Arezzi's ''Wrestling Fans Fantasy Weekend'' convention in August 1990. Despite having no experience in the wrestling business, Abrams was given a budget of $1 million by [[SportsChannel America]] to develop a weekly television series, which would become ''Fury Hour''.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 134.</ref> The first ''Fury Hour'' tapings were held at [[Reseda Country Club]] in the Fall of 1990 and featured established stars such as [[Paul Orndorff]], [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]], [[Don Muraco]], [[Bob Orton, Jr.]], [[Brian Blair]], [[Dan Spivey]], [[Billy Jack Haynes]], [[Ken Patera]], [[Colonel DeBeers]], [[David Sammartino]], [[Ivan Koloff]], and [[Mick Foley|Cactus Jack]].<ref name=mf184>Foley, Mick. Have A Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks (p.184)</ref> The top homegrown talent included \"Wild Thing\" Steve Ray and \"Cutie Pie\" [[Louie Spicolli]]. [[Bruno Sammartino]] and [[Lou Albano]] were hired as commentators.\n\nThe promotion held a taping in [[New York City]] at the [[New York Penta]] in January 1991 that was plagued with legal issues. The World Wrestling Federation sent cease and desist orders after [[The Honky Tonk Man|Honky Tonk Man]] and [[Rick Rude]] appeared on-camera.<ref name=02041991WON>{{cite web|url=https://members.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-newsletter/feb-4-1991-observer-newsletter-pivotal-week-life-dave-meltzer-89881|title=February 4, 1991 Observer Newsletter: Pivotal week in the life of Dave Meltzer|author=Observer Staff|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|website=F4WOnline.com|date=February 4, 1991|accessdate=September 7, 2019}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Both had recently walked out of the WWF but were still under contract to the company. Honky Tonk Man would later explain that the check he received from Abrams for this taping bounced, and he filed a formal complaint with the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] to get reimbursed.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9r6kIfzFSSM</ref>\n\nAbrams hired Howard Brody, the owner of [[Ladies Major League Wrestling]], to help him expand UWF into the Florida market in mid-1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 149.</ref> Following several house shows and a television taping at [[Universal Studios Florida]], Brody was entrusted with finding a venue for the promotion's first [[pay per view]] event in June 1991. Brody suggested the [[Odeum Expo Center]] in Chicago. Abrams insisted on holding [[Beach Brawl]] at [[Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, FL]].<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 156.</ref> The pay per view was a disaster in both attendance and pay per view buys. Following Beach Brawl, Abrams ran one final television taping in Florida before running out of fresh footage for ''Fury Hour''. He struck a deal with Brody to use footage from Ladies Major League Wrestling to fulfill his obligations with SportsChannel America, and the two parted ways in the Fall of 1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 163.</ref>\n\nAbrams would only run three more shows after his initial SportsChannel America deal expired in late 1991. This included a television taping at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] in June 1992 that aired on [[Prime Ticket]] as ''Thunder Hour'', a television taping at [[North Dakota State Fair]] in July 1993 that was never aired, and the [[Blackjack Brawl]] show at [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in September 1994. The latter show aired live on SportsChannel America and was a disaster in both attendance and television ratings.\n\nAbrams left for New York City to take care of his ailing mother in December 1994, and wrestler Al Burke was put in charge of the company.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewalburke.htm</ref> [[Zoogz Rift]] also worked for the company during this time, and claimed Abrams' addiction to [[cocaine]] drained the company of money needed to do further shows.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm</ref> [[ESPN2]] aired old episodes of ''Fury Hour'' and ''Thunder Hour'' in 1995, albeit in heavily edited form. Abrams died of a heart attack in July 1996 while still in New York.\n\nAl Burke claimed ownership of the UWF tape library as abandoned property following the death of Abrams. In recent years, Burke partnered with Todd Okerlund of Classic Wrestling to repackage and license the library through [[DirecTV]] and [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]].\n\n==Major events==\n===Beach Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Beach Brawl}}\nUWF held two major events during its run. The first event, Beach Brawl, was the only pay-per-view event in the company's history and was held on June 7, 1991 at the [[Bradenton Area Convention Center|Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, Florida]]. The event was headlined by a match between [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] and [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], which was the final round match of a sixteen-man tournament for the crowning of the first [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Champion]]. Williams defeated Bigelow to become the first SportsChannel Television Champion. The event was an overall failure with a low buyrate of 0.1 and a crowd of 500 in attendance at the arena.\n\n===Blackjack Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Blackjack Brawl}}\nAfter the failure of Beach Brawl, UWF decided to air a live television special called Blackjack Brawl on September 23, 1994 on [[SportsChannel America]], which was UWF's last major attempt to secure a major television deal and survive in the professional wrestling industry. The event was held at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. Like its predecessor Beach Brawl, the event saw very low attendance of just 600 fans and received negative response from critics and audiences for weak quality, weakly performed matches, nonsense booking and weak commentary. The event featured nine championship matches, with two vacant championships being decided at the event, and seven new championships being contested at the event. The event was headlined by a [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] match between defending champion Steve Williams and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]]. The event was received negatively by fans especially due to the main event match ending in a disqualification, and this was UWF's final show.\n\n==''Fury Hour''==\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name = UWF Fury Hour\n|image = UWF Fury Hour.JPG\n|creator = [[Herb Abrams]]\n|caption = ''UWF Fury Hour'' logo\n|picture_format = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n|camera = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multicamera setup]]\n|runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials)\n|company = Abrams Productions\n|executive_producer = Lenny Duge\n|starring = See [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel|UWF alumni]]\n|country = United States\n|location = [[Reseda Country Club]] <small>(1990)</small><br>[[New York Penta]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[Universal Studios Florida]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[War Memorial Auditorium]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] <small>(1992)</small>\n|network = [[SportsChannel America]] <small>(1990-1991)</small><br>[[Prime Ticket]] <small>(1992)</small><br>[[ESPN2]] <small>(1995)</small>\n|first_aired = October 1, 1990\n|last_aired = July 26, 1992\n|num_episodes = 69\n|list_episodes = List of UWF Fury Hour episodes\n|opentheme = \"[[The Equalizer#Music|The Equalizer Busy Equalizing]]\" by [[Stewart Copeland]]\n|website = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0821416/\n}}\n\nIn 1990, the company signed a one-year television deal with [[SportsChannel America]]. A weekly program called '''''Fury Hour''''' debuted in October 1990, and aired on Monday nights as part of the network's ''Feet, Fists and Fury'' programming block that also included [[kickboxing]] and [[boxing]].<ref>https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/90-OCR/BC-1990-09-17-OCR-Page-0043.pdf</ref>\n\nA famous [[Shoot (professional wrestling)|shoot]] occurred during a semifinal [[UWF Beach Brawl#SportsChannel Television Championship tournament brackets|SportsChannel Television Championship Tournament]] match between Steve Ray and [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] in May 1991. Allegedly, [[Herb Abrams]] thought Ray was sleeping with his wife and paid Williams extra money to rough Ray up during the bout. Ray would claim years later that this was a [[worked shoot]] and both competitors had agreed to work stiff with each other prior to the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm|title=UWF - Interview - Zoogz Rift|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3lkjnUCA7tA|title=Wrestling With Wregret - UWF|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gfwX767OOPY</ref>\n\nAbrams signed a deal with [[Prime Ticket]] in June 1992 for the production and broadcast of new content.<ref>Meltzer, Dave. ''Wrestling Observer Newsletter''. July 6, 1992, p. 14.</ref> New episodes taped at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] aired as '''''Thunder Hour''''' on Sunday nights, and ''Fury Hour'' reruns began airing on Saturday mornings.\n\nIn March 1995, existing ''Fury Hour'' and ''Thunder Hour'' episodes were repackaged to a half-hour format and aired daily on [[ESPN2]]. Those same 24 repackaged episodes later re-aired on [[ESPN Classic]] in 2008 and 2009.<ref>[http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 411mania \u00bb Wrestling \u00bb TV Reports] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922193027/http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 |date=September 22, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/espnclassic.htm|title=UWF - ESPN Classic|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>Steve Ray tried suing ESPN Classic in 2014 for using his likeness during these rebroadcasts, but was unsuccessful.<ref>https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2015/04/espn-win-in-wrestling-footage-case-upheld-on-appeal-592704/</ref>\n\n[[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]] reran original one-hour format episodes of ''Fury Hour'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2004/01/21/320155.html|title=ESPN Classics Canada won't go Raw|publisher=SLAM Wrestling|date=January 21, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Commentators\n!Tenure\n|-\n|[[Herb Abrams]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|September 24, 1990 - November 11, 1990\n|-\n|[[Craig Minervini|Craig DeGeorge]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|December 6, 1990 - July 20, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[Lou Albano]] \n|April 7, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[John Tolos]] \n|June 19, 1992\n|-\n|Carlo Gianelli and John Tolos\n|July 24, 1993 - September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Commissioners===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Commissioner\n! Date started\n! Date finished\n|-\n| Arnold Ross\n| September 24, 1990\n| October 11, 1990\n|-\n| Carlo Gianelli\n| July 24, 1993\n| July 24, 1993\n|-\n| [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n| September 23, 1994\n| September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Recurring segments===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Segment\n! Segment Type\n! Host(s)\n! Years Active\n|-\n|Ask The Wrestlers\n|Interview\n|[[Herb Abrams]]\n|1990 - 1991\n|-\n|Captain Lou's Corner\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]]\n|1990 - 1991\n|-\n|To the Point\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]] and [[Herb Abrams]]\n|1991\n|-\n|Colonel Red's Corner\n|Interview\n|Colonel Red\n|1992\n|-\n|}\n\n==Championships==\n\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Americas Championship|UWF Americas Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship|UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship]] (1993)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Israeli Championship|UWF Israeli Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship|UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF MGM Grand Championship|UWF MGM Grand Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Midget World Championship|UWF Midget World Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF North American Championship|UWF North American Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Southern States Championship|UWF Southern States Championship]] (1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Championship]] (1991-1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Women's World Championship|UWF Women's World Championship]] (1991, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Tag Team Championship|UWF World Tag Team Championship]] (1994)\n\n==Home video==\nIn 1992, the UWF issued six [[VHS]] releases in the United States through Best Film & Video Corporation: ''Beach Brawl'', ''Tag Team Tandems'', ''The Best of Paul Orndorff'', ''The Lumberjack Match'', ''The Steel Cage Match'', and ''Wrestling's Greatest Champions''. In 1993, the UWF released six volumes of [[PAL]] videos in Germany through Summit International Pictures under the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" banner. They were all compilations of Fury Hour matches. The same six \"Wrestling Super Champs\" volumes were re-released in Germany through J\u00fcnger Verlag under the \"Super Wrestling\" banner.\n\nRecent years have seen the emergence of UWF [[DVD]]s in Australia through Payless Entertainment. Each of the seven [[DVD region code#4|Region 4]] DVDs contains one episode of ''Fury Hour''. The DVDs include ''Body Slammin'', ''Grand Slam'', ''Grudge Matches'', ''It's War'', ''Tag Team Madness'', ''The Main Event'', and ''Wrestling Wars''. In Germany, a [[DVD region code|Region 0]] DVD titled \"Wrestling Super 4 Champs\" was released containing two episodes of ''Fury Hour''. Also in Germany, the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" VHS compilations were re-released on DVD in six volumes as \"American History of Wrestling - UWF\".\n\n==Awards==\n*'''Wrestling Observer Newsletter'''\n**1990 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (Herb Abrams)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Promotion of the Year|Worst Promotion of the Year]] (UWF)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Show|Worst Television Show]] (Fury Hour)\n**1994 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Major Wrestling Show|Worst Major Wrestling Show]] (Blackjack Brawl)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/index.htm Herb Abrams' UWF Tribute Site]\n*[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/indy/uwf/uwfindex.html Herb Abrams' UWF] on ProWrestlingHistory.com\n*[https://archive.org/details/HerbAbramsUWF Herb Abrams' UWF] on [[Archive.org]]\n\n{{Professional wrestling in the United States}}\n{{SportsChannel America}}\n{{Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)}}\n\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1996 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:1990s American television series]]\n[[Category:1990 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Companies disestablished in 1996]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:ESPN original programming]]\n[[Category:Independent professional wrestling promotions based in California]]\n[[Category:Marina del Rey, California]]\n[[Category:Prime Sports Network]]\n[[Category:SportsChannel]]\n[[Category:Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)]]\n\n[[de:Universal Wrestling Federation#UWF (Herb Abrams)]]\n", "name_user": "TheNewMinistry", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFury Hour", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_Wrestling_Federation_(Herb_Abrams)"}
{"title_page": "Visa requirements for United States citizens", "text_new": " [[File:Us-passport.jpg|thumb|A [[United States passport]] with biometric chip.]]\n'''Visa requirements for [[United States citizen]]s''' and '''[[U.S. national|non-citizen nationals]]''' are administrative entry restrictions by the authorities of [[Sovereign state|other states]] placed on citizens of the United States.\n\n{{As of|2020|01|7|post=,}} holders of a [[United States passport]] could travel to 184 countries and territories without a [[travel visa]], or with a visa on arrival. The [[United States passport]] currently ranks{{refn|group=Note|name=Ranking| Using [[Ranking#Dense ranking (\"1223\" ranking)|dense ranking]].}} 8th in terms of travel freedom (tied with the passports of Belgium, Greece, Norway and the UK) according to the [[Henley Passport Index]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Ranking \u2013 Visa Passport Index|url=https://www.henleypassportindex.com/assets/2020/Q1/2020%20HPI%20and%20Global%20Mobility%20Report_200107.pdf|publisher=Henley & Partners|accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==2020 travel restrictions==\n{{main|Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:USA Travel Restrictions from COVID-19.svg|thumb|600px|Countries that have imposed some form of travel restrictions on US Citizens and/or travel from the United States]]\nAs a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], several countries have imposed temporary travel restrictions on United States citizens or persons arriving from the United States.<ref name=\"IATA\">[https://www.iatatravelcentre.com/international-travel-document-news/1580226297.htm CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK IN CHINA (PEOPLE'S REP.) - UPDATE], International Air Transport Association Travel Centre</ref>\n*{{flag|Argentina}} \u2014 Admission refused, except residents.\n*{{flag|Austria}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Australia}} \u2014 Admission suspended for non Australians except for Family connection\n*{{flag|Belgium}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Bermuda}} \u2014 14-day self-quarantine required.\n*{{flag|Botswana}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Brunei}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Cambodia}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Canada}} \u2014 Admission refused for nonessential travel.\n*{{flag|Cyprus}} \u2014 Admission refused with few exceptions until April 10.<ref>https://cy.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information/</ref>\n*{{flag|Colombia}} \u2014 Admission refused, except residents who perform an obligatory 14-day period of self isolation.\n*{{flag|Costa Rica}} \u2014 Admission refused until April 12, except residents, who are subject to mandatory 14-day quarantine.\n*{{flag|Czech Republic}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Denmark}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods. Entry refused into Greenland and Faroe Islands until April 13.\n*{{flag|El Salvador}} \u2014 Admission refused, except accredited diplomats and legal residents.\n*{{flag|Estonia}} \u2014 Admission refused effective March 17. Right of entry will remain for citizens and those with a right of residence, as well as foreign citizens whose next of kin live in Estonia. Transit is allowed for foreigners not showing signs of the coronavirus. A mandatory two-week quarantine will be set for anyone entering the country.\n*{{flag|France}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods. Excludes [[overseas departments]] and [[Overseas collectivity|collectivities]].\n*{{flag|Georgia (country)}} - Admission refused until April 21st, except dependents of citizens and diplomats.<ref>https://ge.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information-on-georgia/</ref>\n*{{flag|Germany}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Greece}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Guatemala}} \u2014 Arrivals from U.S. and Canada refused.\n*{{flag|Honduras}} \u2014 Admission refused.<ref>https://hn.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information/</ref>\n*{{flag|Hungary}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Iceland}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|India}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Indonesia}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Italy}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Israel}} \u2014 Admission refused, except by specific permit for non-residents. All entrants must remain under home isolation for 14 days.\n*{{flag|Latvia}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Liechtenstein}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Lithuania}} \u2014 Admission refused, except those with residence permit.\n*{{flag|Luxembourg}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Malaysia}} \u2014 Admission refused for nonresidents. Quarantine required for residents. \n*{{flag|Malta}} \u2014 14-day quarantine required.\n*{{flag|Netherlands}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|New Zealand}} \u2014 14-day self-isolation required.\n*{{flag|North Korea}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Norway}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Oman}} \u2014 Tourist visas suspended until April 15.\n*{{flag|Poland}} \u2014 Admission refused until March 25, except for those possessing residence or work permits. 14 days quarantine required.\n*{{flag|Singapore}} \u2014 Admission refused for nonresidents. Quarantine required for residents. \n*{{flag|Slovakia}} \u2014 Admission refused for nonresidents. Quarantine required for residents. \n*{{flag|Slovenia}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|South Africa}} \u2014 visitors who have been in, transited through, or are nationals of several designated \"high-risk countries\" (including the United States) are not allowed to enter.<ref name=\"ZA-2019-nCov\" />\n*{{flag|Spain}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Suriname}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n*{{flag|Sweden}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Switzerland}} \u2014 Admission to [[schengen area]] refused from noon 17 March until April 16, except residents, family members of EU citizens, medical personnel, and people responsible for transport of goods.\n*{{flag|Ukraine}} \u2014 Admission refused, except residents.<ref>https://ua.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information/</ref>\n*{{flag|UAE}} \u2014 Visa issuance suspended for non-diplomatic passport holders.\n*{{flag|Vietnam}} \u2014 Admission refused.\n\n==Visa requirements map==\n[[File:Visa requirements for United States citizens.png|thumb|upright=3.7|center|Visa requirements for holders of regular United States passports {{legend|#ed1c24|United States}}{{legend|#22b14c|Visa free access}}{{legend|#B5E61D|Visa issued upon arrival}}{{legend|#61c09a|Electronic authorization or online payment required / eVisa}}{{legend|#79D343|Visa available both on arrival or online}}{{legend|#C0C0C0|Visa required prior to arrival}}{{legend|grey|Travel ban imposed by the U.S. federal government}}]]\n\n==Visa requirements==\nGeneral visa requirements of [[List of sovereign states|sovereign countries]] towards United States citizens:\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:18%;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:22%;\"| Visa requirement\n! Allowed stay\n! Notes (excluding departure fees)\n! Reciprocity\n|-\n| {{flag|Afghanistan}}\n| {{no|Visa required}}<ref>{{Timatic|nationality=US|destination=AF|accessdate=26 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/passports/en/country/afghanistan.html|title=Afghanistan|publisher=}}</ref>\n|\n|\n*Visitors born in Afghanistan do not require a visa.\n*Visitors arriving via military air need to legalize their stay if they wish to leave via commercial airline.\n*All visitors are fingerprinted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Afghanistan Count